entry.title: [LCPP] Call TimingPredictor fallback at window.onload or later LCP
entry.content:
LCP Critical Path Predictor(LCPP) learns and predicts what element

would be LCP in the next loading.

LCP TimingPredictor is a callback API that occurs if a LCP

element is painted and predicted as actual LCP(LCP can be reported

twice or more in a load usually.)

This API would be used to delay P2 tasks to improve the actual LCP

timing(or this is our Core Web Vital metric).

Design Doc(google internal):

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1V5PFwVTDonJ1RE52ZI5WGRihn07atHLApnIWsZ3fgfM/edit?pli=1&resourcekey=0-6we9zT_a97B6ZH0jRalL3g



However there are cases that callback is never called or too late.

Then, this CL implements the fallback algorithm

There are 2 cases:

1. At window.onload, LCP occurs multiply before window.onload but no

LCP prediction was hit. Call the fallback at this timing.

2. No LCP occur before window.onload. Call the fallback when the first

LCP occurs after that. There are several factors delay the first LCP

(resource fetch, paint, visible element is put after onload, etc.)



This CL also move the callback implementation from Document to

LCPCriticalPathPredictor to clarify the ownership.

entry.content:
Multiple partitions from the same USB will trigger multiple

addVolume actions, previously when constructing FileData's

children, we only include unprocessed partitions each time

(without prefixKey), this can cause problems:

1. partition1 mounts

2. partition2 mounts, searching for sibling partitions, found

partition1, process partition1 by adding prefixKey

3. partition3 mounts, searching for sibling partitions, nothing

found because both partition1 and partition2 are processed

already.



This CL updates the logic to include processed children into

FileData's children.

entry.title: [Site search policy] Save SEs to keywords DB and TemplateURLService
entry.content:
This CL saves site search engines create by policy to the keywords DB

and to the TemplateURLService. In order to reduce complexity and make

this CL easier to review, some corner cases will be handled by follow-up

CLs, especially:

- Featured search engines (with @ prefix)

- Interaction with DSP set by the user, extension, sync

- Keyword conflicts with search engines set/edited by the user

- Interaction with Sync'ed search engines



Some changes I noticed are required because of this change:

- `TemplateURLServiceFactory` needs to register the preference even if

the feature is disabled - initialization happens too early, making it

harder to test

- `EnterpriseSiteSearchManager` no longer needs to hold the list read

from the pref, so we can simply move it in the call to

`TemplateURLService`

- There is a new class `TemplateURLService::PreLoadingProviders` to

hold DSP and site search data before Web Data loading is completed;

this replaces the `initial_default_search_provider_` pointer, since

now we have many places where we need to check both DSP and site

search.

entry.title: Plumb Page's color providers for painting
entry.content:
This CL plumbs the color providers from Blink::Page to the

WebThemeEngine::Paint method. The color providers in Blink::Page were

introduced in CL:4898493. This is part of our efforts to deprecate the

NativeTheme as a color source.



This CL modifies the WebThemeEngine::Paint function to accept an extra

ColorProvider parameter and update all the its call sites, mainly the

ThemePainterDefault and ScrollbarTheme classes. The CL also adds a

helper method GetColorProvider in the ScrollbarArea class, which

returns the color provider from the document through the LayoutObject.



This CL only passes the color providers to the paint function, but

does not use them yet. The next steps are to update tests to support

the color providers, use them in the paint function and remove the

existing color providers that are currently stored in the

WebThemeEngine.

entry.title: gpu: Prune old TransferCache entries
entry.content:
Business logic changes:

* Transfer cache will post hard-coded 30s delayed task to clear

entries that are older than 30s

* Transfer cache will only have one pending task, but keeps track

of requests to post more tasks while one is pending and post again

when the current pending task runs. This means old entry can live

close to 60s at the longest end.

* Pruning entries is similar to enforcing memory limits.

* "Flush" after pruning at the end, which is implemented by scheduling

GrCacheController to run (with up to 1s delay)

* Change GrCacheController to flush for vulkan as well by flush

(with a callback) and submit.



Changes for experimentation:

* Client side purge kPurgeOldCacheEntriesOnTimer moved to //gpu

* Add new feature kPruneOldTransferCacheEntries

* * If kPurgeOldCacheEntriesOnTimer is disabled, both client and

service side logic are disabled

* * Otherwise, kPruneOldTransferCacheEntries controls whether to use

service- or client-side pruning

* * This is to support hold back experiment for client side purge

* Add kPruneOldTransferCacheEntries to webview flags

* Enable kPruneOldTransferCacheEntries in fieldtrial_testing_config.json

entry.title: Fix :focus invalidation on page focus changes
entry.content:
When we deactivate/activate a page, we do:

1. Clear IsFocused flag of the focused element on deactivating a page

2. Set IsFocused flag of the focused element on activating a page again



However, if an element is focused in an inactive page,

1. The page is deactivated

2. An element is focused, Its IsFocused flag is settings

3. Set IsFocused flag again on activating a page, but :focus style is

not invalidated because IsFocused flag is not changed.



We should invalidate :focus style whenever the page focus state is changed.

entry.title: Do not send FormData objects from the browser to the renderer
entry.content:
Undo removes fields to be sent to the renderer if it does not change

them. Another attribute of FormData is FormData::child_frames which

stores indices of fields in FormData::fields and so removing fields

from the list corrupts this particular data, resulting in mojo parsing

errors.



FormData::child_frames is only needed in

FormForest::UpdateTreeOfRendereForms which is only called in

renderer-to-browser communications.



Other filling functions could also in the future remove fields that are

not to-be filled by the renderer which could be problematic and on a

much larger scale.



This CL fixes the problem by only sending fields and the form renderer

id to the renderer instead of the whole form. This allows us to modify

FormData attributes freely in the browser.



Note that ApplyFormAction was the only mojo function sending a FormData

object from the browser to the renderer.



This CL is a no-op.

entry.title: Move refill logic entirely to the browser process.
entry.content:
The main goal of this CL chain is replacing the FormData object sent via

mojo in ApplyFormAction by a list of FormFieldData objects, which

happens in the last CL of this chain.



Refills are currently detected partially in the browser and partially in

the renderer. This CL moves the entire detection logic to the browser

process.



In more details, prior to this CL:



-The renderer was responsible to not trigger a refill for kUndo filling



-The renderer was responsible to check if the form dynamically changed

in order to figure out whether to trigger the refill or not.



This CL:



-Deletes the FillingContext of a form during Undo on the browser side so

that a refill is not triggered after Undo under any circumstances.



-Adds FillingContext::filled_form so that FillingContext keeps track of

the form used for filling and the browser becomes able to differentiate

between the filled form and the post-filling parsed form to check for

dynamic changes.



-Moves the check of dynamic form change from

AutofillAgent::TriggerRefillIfNeeded to BAM::ShouldTriggerRefill



-Introduces an enum RefillTriggerReason in order to differentiate

between the scenarios where a refill can occur.

entry.title: Reinstate explicitly writing profile data.
entry.content:
When running fuzzers, even if we crash into a CHECK or DCHECK, we want

to record code coverage so that we can display it on the fuzzing code

coverage report.



We had hoped that this would happen by virtue of calling exit()

because we know there's an atexit handler that does this. However, it

seems that libfuzzer's own atexit handler itself immediately exits

thus skipping subsequent atexit handlers. So we need to explicitly dump

out the coverage information.



We still want to retain the call to exit(-1) in these fuzzing cases,

because libfuzzer's own atexit handler is useful in writing out fuzzing

failure cases.

entry.title: Reland: [a11y] Move some of serialization pipeline from RAI to cache.
entry.content:
The previous CL at https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4994320 was reverted due to an issue in clusterfuzz: crbug.com/1505157

It was fixed by making sure any pending tasks to serialize is cancelled on Dispose of AXObjectCacheImpl. The issue stemmed from the fact AXObjectCacheImpl is GCed and thus, any delayed events happening after disposal but not destroyed caused use-after-poison errors.



------ ORIGINAL DESCRIPTION ------

This CL aims to start moving some of the code path starting from HandleAXEvent to ScheduleImmediateAXUpdate over to cache side. The old code is still left in RAI for legacy support.



The aim is to eventually delete the code from RAI side, and then RAI would only be called from ProcessDeferredAccessibilityEvents to AXReadyCallback.



----------------------------

Details (only explaining post-lifecyle mode):

Before this CL, a11y events (kind of) go like this: AXObjectCacheImpl::PostPlatformNotification -> RenderAccessibilityImpl::HandleAXEvent which also calls AXObjectCacheImpl::AddPendingEvent --> RenderAccessibilityImpl::ScheduleImmediateAXUpdate -> AXObjectCacheImpl::ScheduleAXUpdate --> AXObjectCacheImpl::ProcessDeferredAccessibilityEvents -> RenderAccessibilityImpl::AXReadyCallback



Note that -> doesn't mean direct calls. Some calls in the middle may have been skipped. The CL prevents these excessively unnecessary calls in between RAI (RenderAccessibilityImpl) and AXObjectCacheImpl. The calls now go like this (again kinda): AXObjectCacheImpl::PostPlatformNotification -> AXObjectCacheImpl::AddEventToSerializationQueue -> AXObjectCacheImpl::ScheduleImmediateSerialization -> AXObjectCacheImpl::ScheduleAXUpdate -> AXObjectCacheImpl::ProcessDeferredAccessibilityEvents -> RenderAccessibilityImpl::AXReadyCallback



Notice how RAI is only called at the very end. Of course, to make this possible many of the side logic had to be moved too like the delaying code that used to be AXReadyCallback is now at AXObjectCacheImpl::ProcessDeferredAccessibilityEvents.



This image describes the above: https://i.imgur.com/U3tODTX.png

What the CL achieves is moving the code in the blue square over to the left-hand side, thus making the code stay in AXObjectCache longer and only move to RAI at RenderAccessibilityImpl::AXReadyCallback. The serialization delay is moved to ProcessDeferredAccessibilityEvents.



----------------------------

Legacy scheduling mode (as opposed to post-lifecycle serialization) still uses the old code which goes back and forth between RAI and AXObjectCache. The reason they were not moved as well is that legacy mode will get removed eventually anyway. When legacy mode is removed, we can safely remove the old code from RAI.



----------------------------

Also, with the cleaner code, it'll be feasible to change the scheduling logic further to limit some events like scrolling. Scrolling improvements discussed here https://docs.google.com/document/d/1fBK1BBrG8souqZpyv7q_3kxCYF1IYoXNPXmoVL7X8Gk/edit#heading=h.uo8ebdp7cxl



----------------------------

entry.title: Only switch focus state for non-repeat keydown events
entry.content:
Previously any keydown event would activate the focus state. This led to

a weird situation when ALT+CLICK is used to open the context menu. When

ALT is released slowly, the ALT keydown turns into a `repeat` keydown

event and the focus state is activated. However, when ALT is released

quickly, there is no keydown event and the focus state won't be

activated.



Instead only non-repeat keydown events should switch the focus state. So

in both the above situations, the focus state would not be activated.



Bug: b/313711899
